aturalist's eye and methods, Thoreau never rests in the role of observer and collector. Hildebidle sees Thoreau as representative of a long-standing American tendency simultaneously to reject and to use the past, and shows how, as naturalist, he brought together science and literary aims. This gracefully written analysis of Thoreau's thinking and style will well serve all readers of Thoreau and those interested in natural history as a genre.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnglische Literatur Amerikas. 0aNatural history. 0aNature in literature. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aNatural history. 4aThoreau, Henry David, 1817-1862 -- Knowledge -- Natural history. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Science & Technology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067449431240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067449433640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674494336423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674494336/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-HLI